comment: Ms. Heard was blessed with exceptional genetics. This is true of about 10% of the general population. Unfortunately, as you age, the high metabolism that let you eat and drink whatever you liked in your teens and twenties naturally begins to slow as you reach your thirties. I'm 5' 10" and never broke 150 pounds until I was in my forties despite eating like I had a hollow leg. Once the weight gain begins though, it takes either fanatic calorie discipline, and hour or more of regular exercise each day to keep close to your prior body type, and even then you tend to end up packing on ten to twenty pounds each decade. If you don't make the effort weight can come on like an avalanche. She probably never had to make that kind of effort before.

comment:
Remember that Flintstones movie where Rosie O Donnell played Betty Rubble? I was really, really against it, partially because Betty was one of my first childhood crushes and O Donnell... let's just say she had a different shape. 

But I changed my mind when I watched the film, because I felt she at least got Betty's mannerisms right (and especially the laugh). I assume that was the reason she was chosen for the role, rather than anything physical. 

I can get changing a plan for a character because you found an actor or actress who you feel are perfect even if they don't fit the original plan (e.g. if I remember right, Idris Elba was chosen for Heimdall in the MCU because it was felt he brought the appropriate gravitas to the role, the Ben Affleck Daredevil film had Michael Duncan Clarke as an African-American version Kingpin because they thought he had both the appropriate bulk and acting skill to pull it off). 

But I also get why you might fire someone from a role because they no longer suit it. I mean, imagine if someone got hired to play Superman because he's ripped, but then shows up on set all flabby because couldn't be bothered to stay in shape during the lockdowns.
